# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arepa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arepa/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:arepa/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:arepa/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:arepa/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:arepa/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:arepa/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:arepa/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:arepa/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:arepa/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:arepa/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:arepa/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:arepa/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:arepa/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:arepa/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:arepa/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:arepa/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:arepa/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:arepa/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:arepa/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá is the only ritual food required in Candomblé; it is offered to all the orixás in the Candomblé pantheon.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá made of white corn is offered to Oxala; that made of yellow corn is offered to Oxossi.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá is made of white or red corn soaked in water for a day, which is then passed through a mill to make a paste or dough.
[src:arepa/acaçá] The paste or dough is cooked in a pan and stirred continuously to reach a correct consistency.
[src:arepa/acaçá] While warm, small portions of the dough are wrapped in a clean, folded clean banana leaf and passed over a fire.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Finely ground white cornmeal can be substituted for soaked corn.
[src:arepa/acaçá] The acaçá is cut into pieces of equal size.
[src:arepa/acaçá] They are arranged on a platter to be placed on or near a *pegi*, or Candomblé altar.
[src:arepa/acaçá] They also decorate other ritual foods in Candomblé, notably vatapá.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto (Portuguese: *acaçá of black beans*) is a variation of the acaçá made from black beans, i.e., the black turtle bean (*Phaseolus vulgaris*).
[src:arepa/acaçá] Black beans are substituted for soaked corn, similarly made into a paste, wrapped in banana leaves, and steamed in a pan.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto is specifically offered to the god Ogum.
[src:arepa/acaçá] The variation of acaçá is associated with Casa Fanti Ashanti, a Candomblé temple of the Jeje-Nagô tradition in the neighborhood of Cruzeiro do Anil, São Luís, in the state of Maranhão.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá de leite (transl. acaçá of milk) is a fermented drink used in Candomblé rituals.
[src:arepa/acaçá] It is made from a corn mush to which milk and other seasonings are added.
[src:arepa/acaçá] Acaçá de leite is found in Candomblé temples in Bahia and the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:arepa/acaçá] A variation, acaçá de leite de coco, is made from coconut milk.
[src:arepa/acaçá] This variation is found in the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:arepa/alivenci] A form of cheesecake was very popular in Ancient Greece.
[src:arepa/alivenci] The secret of its manufacture was passed during the Roman invasions.
[src:arepa/alivenci] At that time, the Latin name used for this type of cake was placenta that was transmitted in Romanian culture.
[src:arepa/alivenci] For Saint Peter, the Moldovan prepare alivenci.
[src:arepa/aloo-chaat] It can be served as a snack, a side dish or a light meal.
[src:arepa/aloo-chaat] It is made from boiled and fried cubed potatoes served with chat masala.
[src:arepa/aloo-chaat] It is a versatile dish that has many regional variations.
[src:arepa/aloo-chaat] The word *alu* means potatoes in Hindi and the word *chat* is derived from the Hindi word *chatna*, which means 'tasting'.
[src:arepa/aloo-chaat] Thus, 'alu chat' means a savory potato snack.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Although paratha is sometimes said to have originated in Punjabi cuisine, it may have evolved from similar flatbreads from regions connected to India via the Silk Road.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Possible origins include the Persian flatbread *waraki* or from breads introduced by Arabs in India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Sanskrit recipes for versions of paratha appeared in the 12th century.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The popularity of paratha increased during the Mughal Empire, which introduced it across the region.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] During the British imperial era, indentured workers from India introduced paratha to Southeast Asia, the Caribbean, and Mauritius.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In India, several versions of paratha were popularised after the 1947 partition.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is eaten as the central component of a meal, with various accompaniments, often including dahi and pickle.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is eaten for any meal; for breakfast, it is commonly paired with tea.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Some types of paratha are made with spiraling layers, such as lachha paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Stuffed parathas include aloo paratha, using potatoes; gobhi paratha, using cauliflower; mooli paratha, using radish; methi paratha, using fenugreek leaves, and keema paratha, using minced meat.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is also used for wraps, including the kathi roll and paratha roll.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The word *paratha* is from Hindi, derived from the word *para*, meaning 'layer'.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Indian English, the bread is always referred to by the specific term *paratha*, rather than *bread*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The word for paratha differs across India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Alternative spellings include *parantha*, *prantha*, *parata*, *prata*, and *parotta*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is spelled as *palata* (pronounced [pəlàtà]) in Myanmar and *farata* in Mauritius.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the Gulf countries, as well as in East Africa, the breads referred to as chapati are more similar to a paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Like most Indian breads, paratha is wheat-based and unleavened.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The dough is made of atta (whole wheat flour), water, and salt, which is covered in ghee.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Oil may be used instead of ghee, and white flour (maida) may be used instead of whole wheat; maida is used for more tender, flaky parathas.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Vegetables, herbs, and spices may be added; ajowan is a commonly used spice in plain paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The common wheat, the dominant species of wheat in the northern Indian subcontinent, results in the light, spongy texture of North Indian breads such as paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The flour used in paratha is typically of low extraction, although high-extraction flour is sometimes used.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It may also use resultant atta, the coarse byproduct of sifting atta.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In commercial preparations, potato flakes may be used as a binding agent.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is rolled out with oil or ghee, then folded.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] This process of lamination is performed two or more times.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] This usually forms a triangle with four to six layers; it may also be folded into a circle or square.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Stuffed versions of paratha are instead made by shaping the dough into balls and placing a filling inside before rolling them out.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha may be rolled out using a dough sheeting machine that may produce thousands of parathas per hour.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Both plain and stuffed parathas are shallow fried on a tava, a type of iron griddle, until browned, with or without additional ghee.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Sometimes, particularly among street vendors, paratha is fried in a shallow pan filled with oil, thus containing more fat than a paratha cooked on a tava.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha may be brushed with ghee after serving.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] While frying, paratha forms distinct layers.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The lamination of the dough results in a soft, flaky flatbread.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Its lamination process and layered texture are much like a puff pastry, but it does not rise as a puff pastry does.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Frying (rather than baking) results in a slightly crispy outside, and, in the absence of leavening, the formation of steam is responsible for the separation of crust and crumb.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is similar to chapati, with the only difference in physical composition being the use of oil, while paratha also has multiple layers.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is slightly thicker and denser, with a more prominent crumb.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The starch properties of the two breads differ as paratha has fat in its crumb as well as fat coverage that causes more thorough heat transfer.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha has starch granules in its crumb that are deformed and shrunken compared to those of chapati.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The Gujarati bread thepla resembles a cross between paratha and chapati.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is the same size as chapati; a single paratha weighs about 140 grams (4.9 oz).
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Both plain and stuffed parathas are about 15 centimetres (5.9 in) in diameter and 3 mm thick, with plain parathas sometimes ranging to as thin as 2.5 mm.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha has a sturdy texture, enabling it to be served with thick foods.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Stuffed paratha has a softer texture than plain paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is eaten quickly; a study in the journal *Appetite* found that it took about 9 minutes to eat a 250-calorie serving.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] According to a 2020 study in Delhi, the median portion size of paratha is 60 grams, averaging 1 paratha for women and 2 parathas for men.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] According to a 2013 study in the United Kingdom, the mean portion size is 121 grams for children and 100 grams for adults.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha exists in both plain and stuffed varieties.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Dozens of varieties are commonly consumed.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Regional variations differ based on cooking method or filling.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Lachha paratha has circular spiraling layers.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] India has two categories of paratha: North Indian paratha, made from atta, and South Indian parotta, made from maida.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Both are similarly flaky and layered, but the South Indian version achieves this texture through repeated stretching and coiling rather than rolling and folding.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Some versions of paratha have spiraling layers, forming a circle or square.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] 'layered paratha') is a kind of North Indian paratha with many circular layers, formed by shaping a circle of dough into a coil before rolling it out again.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It has a crispy texture and is the same size as a regular paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] *Ulte tave ke paratha* is a North Indian paratha cooked on the bottom side of the pan, the same method as roomali roti.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Cornmeal, atta, palm sugar, ajowan, and green chilli are used to make makkai paratha, while ginger and chilli are used for *adraki mirchi paratha*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Sattu, a type of chickpea flour, is used to make sattu paratha, a breakfast dish eaten in Bihar, Jharkhand, and part of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the Eastern Himalayas, the legume gahat is crushed into a paste that is added to paratha dough.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha has been made with atypical ingredients for nutritional value.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] For example, it may be made with mulberry leaves as a nutritional supplement, which also increases shelf stability of the flour.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Other ingredients that may sometimes be used in the dough include amaranth, flaxseed, sorghum flour, and buckwheat flour.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Many varieties of stuffed paratha exist.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The most common is aloo paratha, with a spiced potato filling.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Aloo paratha uses ingredients such as coriander leaf and green chilli and spices such as amchoor and garam masala, and its proportion of dough to filling may vary.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Along with aloo paratha, the stuffed parathas common in Punjabi cuisine are gobhi paratha, with cauliflower, and mooli paratha, with radish.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Keema paratha uses keema (minced meat), such as lamb, while methi paratha uses fenugreek leaves.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Other common fillings include peas (matar), onions, spinach, and paneer.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Aloo palak paratha contains both potatoes and spinach.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Dal paratha is stuffed with cooked dal such as mung beans.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Sweet parathas include *gurh ka paratha* (jaggery paratha).
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Anda paratha contains beaten eggs; the paratha may simply be coated in eggs, or it may have a filling of eggs, onions, chilli, coriander seed, and ginger added during frying.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Anda paratha is a common Punjabi breakfast.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Among the Sunni Bohras of Gujarat, egg paratha, known as *baida paratha*, is a festive food.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Punjabi cuisine, stuffed parathas are often prepared from leftovers.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] For example, paratha filled with leftover rice dishes is known as *chawal ka paratha*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Bathua paratha has dough mixed with the boiled leaf vegetable bathua and green chilli.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] This is eaten as breakfast in winter in North India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha stuffed with besan (chickpea flour) is known as birahi.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A type of paratha from Chhattisgarh uses a dough with wheat flour, rice flour, and leaf vegetables.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Khoa (milk solids) may also be a paratha filling.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Modern variations of paratha use ingredients such as cheese, mushrooms, or soya, and meat fillings are used for some fusion versions of paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The version eaten in the South Indian cuisines of Karnataka and Tamil Nadu is like a chapati made of maida.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] South Indian variations called Malabar parotta and Ceylon parotta resemble lachha paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Malabar parotta, from the cuisine of Kerala, has layers formed by kneading oil into the dough.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Another preparation from Kerala is kothu parotta, a mixture of chopped parotta with other ingredients.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Veechu parotta is a square-shaped parotta eaten in Tamil Nadu.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Ceylon parotta is similar to this, with the addition of a minced meat filling.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Madurai, Tamil Nadu, has a variant called bun parotta, shaped like a bun.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Bidar, Karnataka, is home to the Bidari paratha, distinguished from regular paratha by the addition of a small amount of semolina flour.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Bengali cuisine, the typical paratha—or *porota*—is triangular and usually combines atta and maida.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] This is common among both Hindu and Muslim Bengalis.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Circular parathas also exist in the region, with five or six layers.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The Dhakai paratha is deep-fried and has many layers, with a hollow centre.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Taking its name from Dhaka, Bangladesh, it is also found in Kolkata, India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Mughlai paratha, a dish from Kolkata, which is prepared by folding a paratha over a filling with beaten eggs and chopped onions, sometimes with minced meat.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is one of the more complex forms of stuffed paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Another Bengali version, petai porota (lit.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] 'beaten paratha'), is tossed and torn apart after cooking, resembling kothu parotta.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is a common street food meal, served with ghugni or aloo dum, and is eaten for breakfast.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Some regions of India serve unique forms of paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] 'layered paratha') is a variant in Awadhi cuisine, originating in Lucknow.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is made of white flour and a large amount of ghee, sometimes with sugar and saffron, and it is folded and rolled.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A type of paratha in eastern Uttar Pradesh and Bihar is called *makhuni*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Dulhan paratha, originating from Hyderabad, Pakistan, is named for its elaborate presentation, which is reminiscent of the ornate appearance of a bride (*dulhan* in Urdu); this dish is known for its combination of flavorful ingredients.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Versions of paratha exist beyond the Indian subcontinent.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Caribbean cuisine features parathas that are milk-based and crispy, known as buss-up-shut.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Trinidad and Tobago, this is classified as a roti, distinguished from other rotis by using more oil.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The roti served in Suriname also evolved from paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The Malaysian variation, roti canai, is a type of South Indian parotta.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The Burmese version, *palata*, may use whole-wheat dough with a filling of peas, served with fried onions on top.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Other Burmese versions include a banana-stuffed version and a pigeon pea-stuffed version known as *bei palata*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The Afghan version, known as *naun-i-parauta*, is leavened and cooked on a griddle.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Sri Lankan cuisine, paratha is known as *godamba roti*.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Like other flatbreads in North Indian cuisine, it is served as the central component of a typical meal; the bread is eaten by using the hands to tear the bread and pick up the accompanying food.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A wide range of foods may be served with paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Common accompaniments include curries, sabzi, pickle, and dahi (curd).
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Likewise, stuffed parathas such as aloo paratha are commonly served with curd or pickle.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] When served by vendors, paratha often comes with dahi or pickle included.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A paratha may also be served with tea or raita, with which it can be rolled up and dipped.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] As a dessert, paratha may be eaten with brown sugar.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Although rice is the staple in Kashmiri cuisine, parathas paired with kofta are a common dish served to guests.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In middle-class Bangladeshi cuisine, paratha is eaten for breakfast or, less commonly, for dinner, while rice is more common for lunch.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the cuisine of Odisha, it is eaten with egg curry for dinner.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the cuisine of Haryana, it may be eaten with mung beans.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Parotta served with beef is a culturally significant dish in Kerala.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is frequently part of a breakfast in North India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A common breakfast in India and Pakistan consists of paratha, butter, and tea, and it may also be eaten alongside eggs.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Karachi, the phrase "chai-paratha" is synonymous with breakfast, and a 1987 survey found that paratha is the most common breakfast food.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha with pickle and curd is also a common breakfast.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A typical breakfast in Uttar Pradeshi Hindu cuisine may pair paratha with a vegetable dish or sweet halva.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Hyderabadi Muslim cuisine, paratha may be paired with eggs or minced meat for breakfast or with a meat dish for lunch.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Stuffed parathas such as aloo paratha, as well as plain parathas, are commonly eaten for breakfast in Punjab and Haryana.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha may be used for wraps, commonly with kebabs.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The kathi roll, originating in Kolkata, is a wrap with a kebab or other toppings served on an egg-covered paratha; This egg-covered paratha in a kathi roll differs from anda paratha, with the egg being scrambled on top of the paratha as it cooks.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Pakistan, particularly in Karachi, a kebab wrapped in paratha is known as a paratha roll.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Lucknow, *ulte tave ke paratha* may be served as a crispy cone, and is the typical pairing with galouti kebab.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The frankie is another wrap using paratha, with various fillings, served as street food in Indian cities.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the United Arab Emirates, paratha is used to make a wrap with potato chips of the brand Chips Oman.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The paratha burger—a hamburger using paratha rather than a hamburger bun—originated in Dubai, at the restaurant Klay by Karak House.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha contains wheat, which provides calories, protein, and minerals and is a major source of carbohydrates.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] As parathas are fried in oil, they have a higher fat content than other flatbreads, The fat content of aloo paratha is about 3.3%, while that of leaf vegetable stuffed parathas has been measured at 5%.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The sodium content may be high, based on the amount of salt added according to consumer preferences.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A 2018 study in Malaysia found high amounts of added sugar in restaurant paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The average commercially produced paratha provides 306 dietary calories per 100 grams.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] This portion contains 44.97 g carbohydrates (including 3.41 g sugar), 11.37 g fat (including 5.23 g saturated fat), 6.92 g protein, 3.96 g fibre, and 371.28 mg salt.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A 100 g serving of a homemade paratha—using the recipe published by the Ministry of Health of Oman—has 394 calories and 13.8 g fat.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Parathas have a high trans fat content of about 7.8%.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The fat content of paratha may contribute to a lower glycemic index than other breads.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The aforementioned homemade paratha has a glycemic index of 32, while methi paratha made with curd and oil has a glycemic index of about 60, lower than that of roti.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha contains a high amount of the vitamin retinol, in part due to the use of ghee.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is also high in iron and vitamin A; the use of palm oil has been shown to increase vitamin A content.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha with additional ingredients can be more nutritionally balanced.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Methi paratha is high in fibre and carotenoids, while bathua paratha is especially high in iron and carotene.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The moisture content of paratha is over 40%.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Due to its short cooking time, paratha experiences low loss of moisture and low deterioration of protein.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It loses about 40% of its weight during cooking.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The use of composite flours has been shown to produce acceptable parathas with increased nutrition.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Parathas, including stuffed parathas, are very perishable due to a high moisture content.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Stuffed parathas experience mold growth in twelve to twenty-four hours.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Thermal processing has been shown to increase the shelf life; however, this may result in hardening, discoloration, and loss of shape.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Irradiation has been shown to preserve paratha for over six months.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Other preservation methods include vacuum packing and additives such as sorbic acid.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Historian Pushpesh Pant writes that there is no evidence of paratha in Ancient India, while historian Chitrita Banerji writes that it "has probably been around in some form or another since antiquity." A theory that paratha originated in Punjabi cuisine is commonly held among Punjabis.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Banerji writes that, despite its association with Punjabi and North Indian cuisine, paratha is often said to be related to poli, a flatbread in Maharashtrian and Gujarati cuisine.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] According to Megha Kohli in *The Bloomsbury Handbook of Indian cuisine*, paratha originated in the city of Peshawar (in modern-day northern Pakistan).
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Trade routes to India, such as the Silk Road, may have introduced flatbreads from Persia and Central Asia, as well as the scallion pancake of Chinese and Uyghur cuisine, which resemble paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The book *Whose Samosa Is It Anyway?* by Sonal Ved suggests that paratha was adapted from the Persian *waraki*, a milk-based flatbread with separating layers.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A theory supported by Pant states that paratha was invented after the arrival of Arabs in India, who merged flatbreads introduced by the Arabs, like roomali and khamiri roti, with the local puri.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Culinary anthropologist Kurush Dalal stated that South Asian parotta came from Central Asia—through maritime trade routes with the Malabar Coast—rather than from North India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha also entered Sri Lankan cuisine from South India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Recipes for various parathas are mentioned in *Manasollasa*, a 12th-century Sanskrit reference work compiled by Someshvara III, a Western Chalukya king who ruled from present-day Karnataka.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Achaya, the parathas listed in this book were more similar to the modern manda roti.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] These included *purana*, which Achaya describes as the modern-day puran poli, as well as stuffed parathas called *manda*, *vestika*, and *pahalika*, the latter being a sweet version.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Bengal, food historian Jayanta Sengupta attributes the introduction of wheat breads like paratha to the thirteenth-century Turkic conquest.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] During the Islamic era, parathas were common with the Muslim nobility and Hindu aristocracy in Punjab, and paratha was also eaten in the Delhi Sultanate.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The Mughal Empire introduced more complex ingredients to the cuisine of the era, used for foods such as paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Mughal cookbooks included recipes for paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It does not appear in the *Nushka-e-Shahjahani*, from the reign of Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan, indicating that it was not yet present.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Banerji states that the Mughals were introduced to parathas during their conquests of Punjab.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The paratha was popular among Mughal leadership, and it later became popular in Islamic Indian cuisine.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It and other flatbreads spread to Dhaka, in Bengal, during this time.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Sweet parathas were also eaten during the Mughal era.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] People from India were sent as indentured workers to Southeast Asia, Mauritius, the Maldives, and the Caribbean, where they introduced paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] This included the British colony in Trinidad, where Indians sent as workers began using white flour for paratha and other flatbreads as a result of European imports.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] On migrant ships to the Caribbean, cooks began using tavas to make large parathas portioned for several people, originating the variation known as paratha roti.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha was introduced to Malaysia around the 1930s by people from the Indian city of Chennai; the term *roti canai* derives from the city's name.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In 19th-century British India, North Indian snack foods such as paratha were eaten as tiffin snacks as part of an early form of Indian fast food.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A similar flatbread, sheermal, is said to have been created as a type of paratha in Lucknow in the 19th century, although it may have originated in Persia.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Bengal, wheat-based foods such as paratha and luchi were primarily for special occasions (such as Ekadashi) before wheat became a staple food, alongside rice, during the 1943 famine.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] During the 1947 partition of India, Punjabi refugees propagated various stuffed parathas, including aloo, gobhi, mooli, methi, and matar, with paneer and keema stuffed versions appearing later.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Pant writes that tandoor-baked paratha was introduced to India during the partition, out of a desire for roti to be less chewy and cold, and that it originated from Amritsari kulcha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Parathas became a common item at dhaba establishments; Pant writes that roadside dhabas invented lachha and pudina parathas.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Some state that the paratha was popularised in Delhi after the partition.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] However, O'Brien suggests this item was prevalent among Punjabis in Delhi before then, and paratha vendors at the Paranthe Wali Gali claim to have been present since the 1880s.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the Caribbean, paratha was one of several dishes from Mughlai cuisine to be widely popularised in the late 20th century.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The world record for the largest paratha, as recognised by the *Guinness World Records*, was set in February 2024 in Amritsar, when chefs from the Taj Swarna hotel created a methi paratha weighing 35 kilograms (77 lb).
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is one of the most common flatbreads in India—alongside chapati and naan—and is the most common that is shallow-fried.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is associated with North Indian cuisine, in which wheat is the predominant staple and atta is particularly common.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] A 2022 study in the South Indian city of Hyderabad found that the average adult consumes 1 paratha, or 40 grams, per day.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Like chapati and puri, paratha is often homemade, as tavas are a common household item.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Ready-to-eat parathas, sold as a convenience food, are a common product in India, as are several types of frozen stuffed paratha.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Ready-to-cook parathas are sold from brands such as Fingerlix.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is frequently sold by vendors at marketplaces, roadsides, and transit stations, as a consistently affordable meal.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is a typical offering at Punjabi dhabas, a type of establishment on highways.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is served also by vendors next to mosques in North India to break the fast on Eid-al-Fitr; they prepare very large parathas that are sliced and served with halwa.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is less common among chefs, except for unusual stuffed versions, according to food writer Vir Sanghvi.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In North Indian Hindu traditions, paratha is classified as pukka, a type of food that is made with ghee, which is associated with purity, and is served when hosting guests or during festivals.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Historically, orthodox Hindus adhered to a pukka diet; those who wanted to limit oil (for health or financial reasons) would cook paratha like chapati, with only a very thin layer of oil applied using a cloth wrapped around a coin.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Uttarakhand, aloo paratha is seen as an energy booster and, when cooked without oil, a cure for a sore throat.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is commonly included in meals in both Indian and Pakistani Punjab, but it is not as common in Gujarat or in North India east of Kanpur.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha, like many breads eaten in North India, is also eaten in Nepali cuisine.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] According to Banerji, stuffed parathas are associated with North Indian cooking but have spread to every Indian city.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Aloo paratha is served across India between Punjab and Bengal.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] It is also common in parts of Pakistan, except in the highlands.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Mooli paratha is common in North India and Kashmir.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is served by many establishments in Delhi.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] The city has parathas that are baked, then fried, which are large enough to serve multiple people.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Old Delhi houses the Paranthe Wali Gali (lit.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] 'Alley of Paratha Makers'), a small lane primarily dedicated to paratha restaurants, where parathas are always stuffed, using ingredients including tomato, lemon, peppers, and papad inside the parathas.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] They are deep-fried in ghee, more similar to stuffed puri or bedmi than typical parathas.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Dhabas of Haryana on the Grand Trunk Road are famous for their parathas, including Sukhdev Dhaba and Gulshan Dhaba in Murthal.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] These dhabas serve Murthal paratha, a version that is deep-fried.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Agra, Uttar Pradesh, an establishment called Ramababu Paratha Bhandhar serves very large parathas, weighing 35 kilograms.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Mauritius, paratha (Morisyen: *farata*) is eaten across all ethnic groups and is known as a homemade comfort food, particularly as a warm food during rainy weather.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In Myanmar, paratha is served at Indian tea shops.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] People in Myanmar eat it on Martyrs' Day, as it was known to be a favorite food of Aung San, whom the holiday celebrates.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] In the Caribbean, paratha, particularly aloo paratha, is among several Indian fast food dishes in the region.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Paratha is widespread in Yemeni and Omani cuisine.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] People in Oman associate it with Omani–Indian culture rather than a specific region of India.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Many Pakistanis in Norway and in Denmark limit their consumption of parathas upon immigrating, eating it as a special breakfast on weekends rather than daily, in part due to health concerns amid changing lifestyles.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Pakistani migrants to the United Kingdom also eat paratha for breakfast, though some members of the community view it as a holdover from Pakistan.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Among Indians in the United States, store-bought parathas are common due to busy lifestyles.
[src:arepa/aloo-paratha] Aloo paratha is commonly served at South Asian dining establishments in the United Kingdom and Pakistani restaurants in South Africa.
[src:arepa/aloo-tikki] Because of the broad geographical distribution of Indian people throughout the world, a number of variations on this dish exist.
[src:arepa/aloo-tikki] In Maharashtra, a popular version of aloo tikki is served with a spicy curry and various chutneys.
[src:arepa/aloo-tikki] It is called ragda pattice and is sold at various chaat stalls throughout the city and especially on Chowpatti Beach.
[src:arepa/aloo-tikki] The aloo tikki in this region is made of mainly locally grown spices such as turmeric, whereas in Bangalore, more coriander is used.
[src:arepa/aloo-tikki] In the United Kingdom, vegetable tikki is available from delicatessen counters at various shops.
[src:arepa/aloo-tikki] Some North Indian dhabas or café-style eateries will sandwich the aloo in bread.
[src:arepa/alpina-productos-alimenticios] In 1945, Max Bazinger and Walter Goggel, two Swiss men arrived in Colombia with the idea of creating a company.
[src:arepa/alpina-productos-alimenticios] They began searching for areas with rich milk collection and when they encountered Sopó valley, they were fascinated by its similarity to the Swiss landscape.
[src:arepa/alpina-productos-alimenticios] At the time, they bought 500 bottles of milk and with them, they manually produced their dairy products.
[src:arepa/alpina-productos-alimenticios] After obtaining a bank loan, they acquired 11 acres of land to build their first factory.
[src:arepa/alpina-productos-alimenticios] In December 2021, Alpina acquired 70% of Clover Sonoma.
[src:arepa/arepa] Arepa can be served with accompaniments, such as cheese, *cuajada*, various types of meat, avocado, or *diablito* (deviled ham spread).
[src:arepa/arepa] It can also be split to make sandwiches.
[src:arepa/arepa] Sizes, maize types, and added ingredients vary based on preparation.
[src:arepa/arepa] It is similar to the Mexican *gordita,* the Salvadoran pupusa, the Ecuadorian *tortilla de maíz*, and the Panamanian *tortilla* or *changa*.
[src:arepa/arepa] The *arepa* is a pre-Columbian dish from the area that is now Colombia, Panama and Venezuela.
[src:arepa/arepa] Instruments used to make flour for the *arepas*, and the clay slabs on which they were cooked, were often found at archaeological sites in the area.
[src:arepa/arepa] Although it has not been specified in which country an **arepa** was cooked for the first time, it has been possible to define the oldest dates of the presence of maize in Colombia and Venezuela.
[src:arepa/arepa] For example, in Colombia, the first record of the presence of corn cultivation dates from about 6,000 years ago.
[src:arepa/arepa] However, the presence of arepas dates from 3,000 years ago (specifically in the Altiplano Cundiboyacense by the Muisca), while in Venezuela, the estimate is about 2,800 years ago.
[src:arepa/arepa] Throughout its history, the **arepa** has stayed mainly unchanged from the **arepas** that pre-Columbian native peoples would have consumed, making the **arepa** one of the few pre-contact traditions that have remained popular in the years since colonization.
[src:arepa/arepa] The name **arepa** is related to *erepa*, the word for 'cornbread' in the Cumanagoto language.
[src:arepa/arepa] The **arepa** is a flat, round, unleavened patty of soaked, ground kernels of maize, or—more frequently nowadays—maize meal or maize flour.
[src:arepa/arepa] It can be grilled, baked, fried, boiled, or steamed.
[src:arepa/arepa] The characteristics vary by color, flavor, size, and the food with which it may be stuffed, depending on the region.
[src:arepa/arepa] Simple **arepas** are filled with butter or cheese and baked.
[src:arepa/arepa] Depending on the meal, more filling varieties can be added with combinations of ingredients like beans, meat, avocados, eggs, tomatoes, salad, shrimp, or fish.
[src:arepa/arepa] Fried **arepas** are often consumed in northern South America, filled with white cheese on top and served with fried eggs.
[src:arepa/arepa] Sweet fried **arepas** are another variety often prepared with sugarloaf (*papelón*) and anise (*anís*).
[src:arepa/arepa] Venezuelan white cheese is another topping for fried *arepas* that can be combined with feta cheese.
[src:arepa/arepa] Initially, *arepa* flour was made by grinding maize at home.
[src:arepa/arepa] In the 1950s, precooked *arepa* flour was invented by Dr.
[src:arepa/arepa] Luis Caballero Mejías, a Venezuelan engineer, and became an instant success.
[src:arepa/arepa] The flour is mixed with water and salt, and occasionally oil, butter, eggs or milk.
[src:arepa/arepa] Because the flour is already cooked, the blend forms into patties easily.
[src:arepa/arepa] After being kneaded and formed, the patties are fried, grilled, or baked.
[src:arepa/arepa] Some varieties of *arepas* are made with "peeled" corn using the nixtamalization process; they are known as *arepa pelada*.
[src:arepa/arepa] However, in countries such as Colombia, it is not common to reconstitute corn flour as it is in Venezuela.
[src:arepa/arepa] Thus, in Colombia, it is more common to see pre-roasted arepas ready for consumption in stores and supermarkets, giving rise to an industry that in 2019 alone had sales of USD $124 million with companies such as Arepas Sary and Alpina Productos Alimenticios.
[src:arepa/arepa] According to food anthropologist Ocarina Castillo of the Central University of Venezuela, the dish is likely thousands of years old and originated in the region now occupied by the two countries before colonizers of the area drew borders.
[src:arepa/arepa] There are different ways to prepare *arepas*, but one of the most traditional is the Cotoca recipe.
[src:arepa/arepa] Several varieties of *arepa* can be found in the country, such as the Cruceña and Andina varieties.
[src:arepa/arepa] The first record of the existence of arepas dates from about 3,000 years ago in what is currently Colombia.
[src:arepa/arepa] The *arepa* is an iconic food in Colombia, with some 75 distinct preparation forms.
[src:arepa/arepa] According to a study conducted by the Colombian Academy of Gastronomy, the *arepa* is part of the Colombian cultural heritage and can be considered a symbol of national gastronomic unity.
[src:arepa/arepa] In 2006, the *arepa* was named the cultural symbol of Colombia in a competition organized by *Semana* magazine with support from Caracol Televisión, the Ministry of Culture and 'Colombia is Passion'.
[src:arepa/arepa] In the Paisa region, the *arepa* is especially important to the local people and sometimes accompanies all meals of the day.
[src:arepa/arepa] In addition, *arepas* are strung into necklaces and placed around the necks of honored dignitaries as a sign of praise.
[src:arepa/arepa] Many varieties of *arepa* were introduced from this region.
[src:arepa/arepa] In Colombia, the *arepa* is sold commercially in neighborhood stores, chain supermarkets, and market plazas and packaged with preservatives as a pre-molded white or yellow corn dough ready to grill or fry at home.
[src:arepa/arepa] It is also sold in the form of industrialized corn flour that requires hydration before preparation.
[src:arepa/arepa] In addition, *arepas* are sold by street vendors, in cafeterias, and in neighborhood stores.
[src:arepa/arepa] Restaurants of the Paisa Region offer a wide variety of *arepas*, including a unique style of stuffed *arepa* that can be filled with eggs, meat, or cheese.
[src:arepa/arepa] Colombians in the Caribbean region commonly eat a breakfast variation called *arepa con huevo*, which consists of a cooked *arepa* which has been split open, stuffed with a raw egg, and fried.
[src:arepa/arepa] The Colombian Arepa Festival is celebrated in Barranquilla, Bogotá, Bucaramanga, Cali and Medellín.
[src:arepa/arepa] Each city takes turns organizing the festival between August and December.
[src:arepa/arepa] There are also many other types of arepas, including arepa de choclo, arepa de queso, arepa frita, arepa costeña, arepa de yuca, and arepa paisa.
[src:arepa/arepa] Some recipes for this type of **arepa** can contain *doble crema* cheese and chicken.
[src:arepa/arepa] One of its characteristics is that it is relatively thin unlike other *arepas* and also has a toasted and golden colored shell.
[src:arepa/arepa] Another variation is the **arepa* boyacense*, with the Municipality of Ventaquemada being one of the most outstanding in terms of its production.
[src:arepa/arepa] This type of **arepa** may contain butter, eggs, and cheese.
[src:arepa/arepa] It has a certain sweetness, and in some recipes, this **arepa** may have *cuajada*.
[src:arepa/arepa] There is also the **arepa* paisa*, which is consumed in the Department of Antioquia.
[src:arepa/arepa] It is prepared with *maíz trillado* (lit.
[src:arepa/arepa] This form most closely resembles indigenous cuisine.
[src:arepa/arepa] In addition, another **arepa** variation consumed in the Andean region of the country is the **arepa* santandereana*, which contains cooked yuca and *chicharrón*.
[src:arepa/arepa] In the Province of Guanacaste, **arepas** are prepared in the form of large, toasted sponge cakes, seasoned with *Bagaces* type cheese.
[src:arepa/arepa] In Cartago, during colonial times, *arepas* were filled with pork.
[src:arepa/arepa] In Puerto Rico, mainly in the San Juan area and beach sides, *arepas* are popular.
[src:arepa/arepa] They can also be found in some restaurants, almost always as *arepas de coco*.
[src:arepa/arepa] The Puerto Rican *arepa* is made with wheat flour, coconut milk, coconut oil, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:arepa/arepa] They can be fried, baked, or cooked on a grill.
[src:arepa/arepa] Once done, the *arepa* is cut open and stuffed.
[src:arepa/arepa] Crab, shrimp, and octopus stewed in sofrito, lemon, coconut milk, and ginger, among other ingredients, are the most popular.
[src:arepa/arepa] The arepa is a symbol of Venezuelan gastronomy and one of the most common pre-Hispanic foods still popular in Venezuela.
[src:arepa/arepa] The first records of this dish are about 2,800 years ago.
[src:arepa/arepa] According to a 2015 survey of the Venezuelan people, nearly 70 percent of the nation ate **arepas** regularly.
[src:arepa/arepa] It is common for Venezuelans to eat **arepas** throughout the day, both as snacks and as sides to meals, creating a culture where these corn products (Harina PAN) can be found almost everywhere and in specific restaurants called *areperas*.
[src:arepa/arepa] The **arepa** is seen as a cornerstone of a Venezuelan diet; prior to the 2015 food shortages, it was estimated that each year the average Venezuelan consumed about 30 kilos of the corn flour used to make **arepas**.
[src:arepa/arepa] Venezuelan *arepas* are commonly filled with a great variety of different fillings, from beef and avocado to cheese, varying widely by the location of where they are sold and the ingredients that can be obtained.
[src:arepa/arepa] In Venezuela's Andes region, *arepas de trigo* are made with wheat flour rather than cornmeal.
[src:arepa/arepa] These lighter **arepas** are generally eaten as a snack or an accompaniment to heavier meals.
[src:arepa/arepa] Former Venezuelan president Nicolás Maduro "has tried to use arepas as a nationalist rallying point, if not a political tool, claiming the food is from his country alone", according to the *New York Times*.
